@merket yes. 16 families built 16 houses. Each house was built up to certain milestone. Teams would switch to another house. Round n round.
@troutgirl ah yes. You used moo IIRC?
@troutgirl ownership? Sense of mastery?
@Quan I'm glad she found an outlet. Watching your parent's friends pass is heartbreaking. Like a world getting smaller by the day.
15/ The house we built together is what saved my family. Me.
14/ As a family unit, we still aren't all financially literate, still struggling or repeating unhealthy patterns, and still learning.
13/ I went to college for free thanks to FAFSA, mom's $7000 a year part-time job, and Native Hawaiian programs from Kamehameha.
12/ My story only improved after mom made it out of housing. She found a government subsidized project that helps people build a house.
11/ I lived in a housing complex in Hawaii called Puu Wai Momi, Halawa housing, by the Stadium. It was a big deal when Kmart opened nearby.
10/ You rattle off nicknames, family names, friends of friends brother's names to avoid getting your front teeth knocked out for a dollar.
9/ There was always a gang to join. See, if your dad is a goon (huge Samoan guy) you can use his name to avoid lots of conflict.
8/ We never had enough. We never saved. We never went on vacations. I wore hand me down clothes from my grandma's boss.
@ericnakagawa 7/ Forcing my mom to account for every single penny while he spent excessively on alcohol and cigarettes.
6/ Eventually, other worse things arise out of abusive relationships: Socially cutting off my mother from friends until she was friendless.
5/ The physical violence at the time seemed to be the worst thing. Much of it driven by my step dad's job losses and alcoholism.
4/ I was the big brother. I would huddle the kids up in one room while we waited and hoped for the yelling to subside.
3/ The hardest part of growing up wasn't the hunger. Domestic violence really was the worst. Especially with babies in the house.
2/ We lived off WIC, subsidized food, and food stamps. In Hawaii, you have to always be humble even at parties when you are starving.
1/ I was raised by a single mother. I'm one of eight children, from three different dads, section 8 housing. We were always broke.
